abstract = {Few micro\ldots nance-funded businesses grow beyond subsistence entrepreneur- ship. This paper considers one possible explanation: that the structure of existing micro\ldots nance contracts may discourage risky but high-expected return investments. To explore this possibility, I develop a theory that uni\ldots es models of investment choice, informal risk sharing, and formal \ldots nancial contracts. I then test the predictions of this theory using a series of experiments with clients of a large micro\ldots nance institution in India. The experiments con\ldots rm the theo- retical predictions that joint liability creates two ine¢ ciencies. First, borrowers free-ride on their partners, making risky investments without compensating partners for this risk. Second, the addition of peer-monitoring overcompen- sates, leading to sharp reductions in risk-taking and pro\ldots tability. Equity-like \ldots nancing, in which partners share both the bene\ldots ts and risks of more pro\ldots table projects, overcomes both of these ine¢ ciencies and merits further testing in the \ldots eld.},
annote = {Theoretical model of investment choice under different microfinance contracts. Risk-averse borrowers choose how much to allocate to a safe and risky project with higher expected return. Possibility of informal insurance up to a credible amount (cannot credibly commit to transfer more than the value of the insurance scheme). Does not allow for strategic default or savings.
Insurance increases incentive to take risks, but increases the incentive to try to prevent partner from taking risks. Risk-taking increases the incentive to engage in informal insurance (higher expected returns so more to share around, but higher risk so more demand for sharing).
        
Joint liability (mandatory transfers since no strategic default) increases risk taking by free-riding on partner's insurance, since cannot credibly commit to share returns on project. Partners may reduce own risk-taking in response to risk taking by the other member. However if the other member takes on too much risk, I will also take on too much (since nobody can pay in the bad state due to limited liability).
        
Full, enforced insurance through "equity contract", borrowers internalise the cost of insurance so removing the distortion from JL and increase risk-taking relative to IL, attaining constrained Pareto optimal.
        
Cooperation considered in terms of the amount of informal insurance and coordinating on project choice. 
        
Actual transfers well short of constrained PO - perhaps use another eqm selection (e.g. risk-dominance, Harsanyi \& Selten)
Much more informal insurance under full information, as predicted.
More informal insurance under JL
Informal transfers seem to be dynamic, not just a static strategy. Look more like loans than one-off transfers. May help relax IC constraint and increase scope for informal insurance.
Informal insurance does not increase risk taking
Under JL, full info leads to slight reduction in risk-taking. Incomplete info leads to increase in risk-taking, particularly by the more risk-tolerant.
Explicit approval rights are used to reduce risk taking under incomplete information.
Equity contracts increase expected returns.
        
        
Useful empirical stuff:
-Only one round is chosen and paid out to prevent self-insurance across rounds (Charness and Genicot 2007)
-Identify risk preferences by choice from menu of lotteries
-Wilcoxon rank-sum tests?},
author = {Fischer, Greg},
journal = {mimeo},
keywords = {Experimental,Field Experiment,Group lending,Insurance,Joint Liability,Microfinance,Project choice,Repayment,Risk sharing,Theoretical},
mendeley-tags = {Experimental,Field Experiment,Group lending,Insurance,Joint Liability,Microfinance,Project choice,Repayment,Risk sharing,Theoretical},
title = {{Contract structure, risk sharing, and investment choice}},
year = {2010}
}
